HOUSE BILL DRH40122-ML-70
Short Title: Revise Laws on Domestic & Child Abuse. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Blackwell.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ALLOW A JUDGE TO ISSUE A PERMANENT NO CONTACT ORDER
3 AGAINST A DEFENDANT CONVICTED OF CERTAIN VIOLENT OFFENSES AND
4 TO PROVIDE THAT IT IS FELONY CHILD ABUSE FOR ANY PERSON PROVIDING
5 CARE TO OR SUPERVISION OF A CHILD LESS THAN SIXTEEN YEARS OF AGE TO
6 COMMIT OR ALLOW THE COMMISSION OF A SEXUAL ACT UPON THE CHILD.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 PART I. ALLOWING JUDGE TO ISSUE A PERMANENT NO CONTACT ORDER
10 AGAINST A DEFENDANT CONVICTED OF CERTAIN VIOLENT OFFENSES
11 SECTION 1.(a) Article 81D of Chapter 15A of the General Statutes reads as
12 rewritten:
13 "Article 81D.
14 "Permanent No Contact Order Against Convicted Sex Violent Offender.
15 "§ 15A-1340.50. Permanent no contact order prohibiting future contact by convicted sex
16 violent offender with crime victim.
17 (a) The following definitions apply in this Article:
18 (1) Permanent no contact order. – A permanent injunction that prohibits any
19 contact by a defendant with the victim of the sex violent offense for which the
20 defendant is convicted. convicted, or with the victim's immediate family. The
21 duration of the injunction is the lifetime of the defendant.
22 (2) Sex offense. – Any criminal offense that requires registration under Article
23 27A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes.
24 (3) Victim. – The person against whom the sex violent offense was committed.
25 (4) Violent offense. – Any of the following:
26 a. A criminal offense that requires registration under Article 27A of
27 Chapter 14 of the General Statutes.
28 b. A Class A through G felony that is not otherwise covered under
29 sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision.
30 c. An offense under subsection (b) of G.S. 14-32.4.
31 (b) When sentencing a defendant convicted of a sex violent offense, the judge, at the
32 request of the district attorney, shall determine whether to issue a permanent no contact order.
33 The judge shall order the defendant to show cause why a permanent no contact order shall not be
34 issued and shall hold a show cause hearing as part of the sentencing procedures for the defendant.
35 …
*DRH40122-ML-70*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) At the conclusion of the show cause hearing the judge shall enter a finding for or
2 against the defendant. If the judge determines that reasonable grounds exist for the victim to fear
3 any future contact with the defendant, the judge shall issue the permanent no contact order. The
4 judge shall enter written findings of fact and the grounds on which the permanent no contact
5 order is issued. The no contact order shall be incorporated into the judgment imposing the
6 sentence on the defendant for the conviction of the sex violent offense.
7 …."
8 SECTION 1.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
9 offenses committed on or after that date.
10
11 PART II. CLARIFYING CHANGES TO FELONY CHILD ABUSE LAWS
12 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 14-318.4 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 14-318.4. Child abuse a felony.
14 (a) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
15 years of age who intentionally inflicts any serious physical injury upon or to the child or who
16 intentionally commits an assault upon the child which results in any serious physical injury to
17 the child is guilty of a Class D felony, except as otherwise provided in subsection (a3) of this
18 section.
19 (a1) Any A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
20 16 years of age, or any other person providing care to or supervision of the child, age who
21 commits, permits, or encourages any act of prostitution with or by the child is guilty of child
22 abuse and shall be punished as a Class D felon.
23 (a2) Any A parent or legal guardian of any other person providing care to or supervision
24 of a child less than 16 years of age who commits or allows the commission of any sexual act
25 upon the child is guilty of a Class D felony.
26 (a3) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
27 years of age who intentionally inflicts any serious bodily injury to the child or who intentionally
28 commits an assault upon the child which results in any serious bodily injury to the child, or which
29 results in permanent or protracted loss or impairment of any mental or emotional function of the
30 child, is guilty of a Class B2 felony.
31 (a4) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
32 years of age who, for the purpose of causing fear, emotional injury, or deriving sexual
33 gratification, intentionally and routinely (i) inflicts physical injury on that child and (ii) deprives
34 that child of necessary food, clothing, shelter, or proper physical care is guilty of a Class B2
35 felony.
36 (a4)(a5) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
37 16 years of age whose willful act or grossly negligent omission in the care of the child shows a
38 reckless disregard for human life is guilty of a Class E felony if the act or omission results in
39 serious bodily injury to the child.
40 (a5)(a7) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
41 16 years of age whose willful act or grossly negligent omission in the care of the child shows a
42 reckless disregard for human life is guilty of a Class G felony if the act or omission results in
43 serious physical injury to the child.
44 (a6) For purposes of this section, a "grossly negligent omission" in providing care to or
45 supervision of a child includes the failure to report a child as missing to law enforcement as
46 provided in G.S. 14-318.5(b).
47 (b) The felony of child abuse is an offense additional to other civil and criminal
48 provisions and is not intended to repeal or preclude any other sanctions or remedies.
49 (c) Abandonment of an infant less than seven days of age pursuant to G.S. 14-322.3 may
50 be treated as a mitigating factor in sentencing for a conviction under this section involving that
51 infant.
Page 2 DRH40122-ML-70

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) The following definitions apply in this section:
2 (1) Grossly negligent omission. – In the context of providing care to or
3 supervision of a child, this term includes the failure to report a child as missing
4 to law enforcement as provided in G.S. 14-318.5(b).
5 (2) Serious bodily injury. – Bodily injury that creates a substantial risk of death
6 or that causes serious permanent disfigurement, coma, a permanent or
7 protracted condition that causes extreme pain, or permanent or protracted loss
8 or impairment of the function of any bodily member or organ, or that results
9 in prolonged hospitalization.
10 (2)(3) Serious physical injury. – Physical injury that causes great pain and suffering.
11 The term includes serious mental injury."
12 SECTION 2.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
13 offenses committed on or after that date.
14
15 PART III. SAVINGS CLAUSE & EFFECTIVE DATE
16 SECTION 3.(a) Prosecutions for offenses committed before the effective date of
17 this act are not abated or affected by this act, and the statutes that would be applicable but for
18 this act remain applicable to those prosecutions.
19 SECTION 3.(b) Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
20 law.
